<doc id="17944" wikidata="Q664495" url="?curid=17944" title="Lie algebra">
<text>In mathematics, a Lie algebra (pronounced ) is a vector space formula_1 together with an operation called the Lie bracket, an alternating bilinear map formula_2, that satisfies the Jacobi identity. In other words, a Lie algebra is an algebra over a field for which the multiplication operation (called the Lie bracket) is alternating and satisfies the Jacobi identity. The Lie bracket of two vectors formula_3 and formula_4 is denoted formula_5. A Lie algebra is typically a non-associative algebra. However, every associative algebra gives rise to a Lie algebra, consisting of the same vector space with the commutator Lie bracket, formula_6.

Lie algebras are closely related to Lie groups, which are groups that are also smooth manifolds: every Lie group gives rise to a Lie algebra, which is the tangent space at the identity. (In this case, the Lie bracket measures the failure of commutativity for the Lie group.) Conversely, to any finite-dimensional Lie algebra over the real or complex numbers, there is a corresponding connected Lie group, unique up to covering spaces (Lie&#x27;s third theorem). This correspondence allows one to study the structure and classification of Lie groups in terms of Lie algebras, which are simpler objects of linear algebra.

In more detail: for any Lie group, the multiplication operation near the identity element 1 is commutative to first order. In other words, every Lie group &quot;G&quot; is (to first order) approximately a real vector space, namely the tangent space formula_7 to &quot;G&quot; at the identity. To second order, the group operation may be non-commutative, and the second-order terms describing the non-commutativity of &quot;G&quot; near the identity give formula_7 the structure of a Lie algebra. It is a remarkable fact that these second-order terms (the Lie algebra) completely determine the group structure of &quot;G&quot; near the identity. They even determine &quot;G&quot; globally, up to covering spaces.

In physics, Lie groups appear as symmetry groups of physical systems, and their Lie algebras (tangent vectors near the identity) may be thought of as infinitesimal symmetry motions. Thus Lie algebras and their representations are used extensively in physics, notably in quantum mechanics and particle physics.

An elementary example (not directly coming from an associative algebra) is the 3-dimensional space formula_9 with Lie bracket defined by the cross product formula_10 This is skew-symmetric since formula_11, and instead of associativity it satisfies the Jacobi identity:
:formula_12
This is the Lie algebra of the Lie group of rotations of space, and each vector formula_13 may be pictured as an infinitesimal rotation around the axis formula_14, with angular speed equal to the magnitude
of formula_14. The Lie bracket is a measure of the non-commutativity between two rotations. Since a rotation commutes with itself, one has the alternating property formula_16.

== History ==
Lie algebras were introduced to study the concept of infinitesimal transformations by Sophus Lie in the 1870s, and independently discovered by Wilhelm Killing in the 1880s. The name &quot;Lie algebra&quot; was given by Hermann Weyl in the 1930s; in older texts, the term &quot;infinitesimal group&quot; was used.

==Definition of a Lie algebra==
A Lie algebra is a vector space formula_17 over a field formula_18 together with a binary operation formula_19 called the Lie bracket, satisfying the following axioms:

* &quot;Bilinearity&quot;,
::formula_20
::formula_21
:for all scalars formula_22 in formula_18 and all elements formula_24 in formula_7.

* The &quot;Alternating&quot; property,
::formula_26
:for all formula_3 in formula_7.

* The &quot;Jacobi identity&quot;,
:: formula_29
:for all formula_24 in formula_7.

Given a Lie group, the Jacobi identity for its Lie algebra follows from the associativity of the group operation.

Using bilinearity to expand the Lie bracket formula_32 and using the alternating property shows that formula_33 for all formula_34 in formula_7. Thus bilinearity and the alternating property together imply
* Anticommutativity,
:: formula_36
:for all formula_34 in formula_7. If the field does not have characteristic 2, then anticommutativity implies the alternating property, since it implies formula_39

It is customary to denote a Lie algebra by a lower-case fraktur letter such as formula_40. If a Lie algebra is associated with a Lie group, then the algebra is denoted by the fraktur version of the group&#x27;s name: for example, the Lie algebra of SU(&quot;n&quot;) is formula_41.

===Generators and dimension===
The &quot;dimension&quot; of a Lie algebra over a field means its dimension as a vector space. In physics, a vector space basis of the Lie algebra of a Lie group &quot;G&quot; may be called a set of &quot;generators&quot; for &quot;G&quot;. (They are &quot;infinitesimal generators&quot; for &quot;G&quot;, so to speak.) In mathematics, a set &quot;S&quot; of &quot;generators&quot; for a Lie algebra formula_7 means a subset of formula_7 such that any Lie subalgebra (as defined below) that contains &quot;S&quot; must be all of formula_7. Equivalently, formula_7 is spanned (as a vector space) by all iterated brackets of elements of &quot;S&quot;.

== Basic examples ==
===Abelian Lie algebras===
Any vector space formula_46 endowed with the identically zero Lie bracket becomes a Lie algebra. Such a Lie algebra is called abelian. Every one-dimensional Lie algebra is abelian, by the alternating property of the Lie bracket.

=== The Lie algebra of matrices ===
* On an associative algebra formula_47 over a field formula_18 with multiplication written as formula_49, a Lie bracket may be defined by the commutator formula_50. With this bracket, formula_47 is a Lie algebra. (The Jacobi identity follows from the associativity of the multiplication on formula_47.) 
* The endomorphism ring of an formula_18-vector space formula_46 with the above Lie bracket is denoted formula_55.
*For a field &quot;F&quot; and a positive integer &quot;n&quot;, the space of &quot;n&quot; × &quot;n&quot; matrices over &quot;F&quot;, denoted formula_56 or formula_57, is a Lie algebra with bracket given by the commutator of matrices: formula_58. This is a special case of the previous example; it is a key example of a Lie algebra. It is called the general linear Lie algebra.

:When &quot;F&quot; is the real numbers, formula_59 is the Lie algebra of the general linear group formula_60, the group of invertible &quot;n&quot; x &quot;n&quot; real matrices (or equivalently, matrices with nonzero determinant), where the group operation is matrix multiplication. Likewise, formula_61 is the Lie algebra of the complex Lie group formula_62. The Lie bracket on formula_63 describes the failure of commutativity for matrix multiplication, or equivalently for the composition of linear maps. For any field &quot;F&quot;, formula_64 can be viewed as the Lie algebra of the algebraic group formula_65 over &quot;F&quot;.

==Definitions==
=== Subalgebras, ideals and homomorphisms ===
The Lie bracket is not required to be associative, meaning that formula_66 need not be equal to formula_67. Nonetheless, much of the terminology for associative rings and algebras (and also for groups) has analogs for Lie algebras. A Lie subalgebra is a linear subspace formula_68 which is closed under the Lie bracket. An ideal formula_69 is a linear subspace that satisfies the stronger condition:
:formula_70

In the correspondence between Lie groups and Lie algebras, subgroups correspond to Lie subalgebras, and normal subgroups correspond to ideals.

A Lie algebra homomorphism is a linear map compatible with the respective Lie brackets:
:formula_71
An isomorphism of Lie algebras is a bijective homomorphism.

As with normal subgroups in groups, ideals in Lie algebras are precisely the kernels of homomorphisms. Given a Lie algebra formula_7 and an ideal formula_73 in it, the &quot;quotient Lie algebra&quot; formula_74 is defined, with a surjective homomorphism formula_75 of Lie algebras. The first isomorphism theorem holds for Lie algebras: for any homomorphism formula_76 of Lie algebras, the image of formula_77 is a Lie subalgebra of formula_78 that is isomorphic to formula_79.

For the Lie algebra of a Lie group, the Lie bracket is a kind of infinitesimal commutator. As a result, for any Lie algebra, two elements formula_80 are said to &quot;commute&quot; if their bracket vanishes: formula_81.

The centralizer subalgebra of a subset formula_82 is the set of elements commuting with &quot;formula_83&quot;: that is, formula_84. The centralizer of formula_7 itself is the &quot;center&quot; formula_86. Similarly, for a subspace &quot;S&quot;, the normalizer subalgebra of &quot;formula_83&quot; is formula_88. If formula_83 is a Lie subalgebra, formula_90 is the largest subalgebra such that formula_83 is an ideal of formula_90.

==== Example ====
The subspace formula_93 of diagonal matrices in formula_64 is an abelian Lie subalgebra. (It is a Cartan subalgebra of formula_95, analogous to a maximal torus in the theory of compact Lie groups.) Here formula_93 is not an ideal in formula_95 for formula_98. For example, when formula_99, this follows from the calculation:
formula_100
(which is not always in formula_101).

Every one-dimensional linear subspace of a Lie algebra formula_7 is an abelian Lie subalgebra, but it need not be an ideal.

=== Product and semidirect product ===
For two Lie algebras formula_7 and formula_104, the &quot;product&quot; Lie algebra is the vector space formula_105 consisting of all ordered pairs formula_106, with Lie bracket
:formula_107
This is the product in the category of Lie algebras. Note that the copies of formula_1 and formula_109 in formula_105 commute with each other: formula_111

Let formula_7 be a Lie algebra and formula_113 an ideal of formula_7. If the canonical map formula_115 splits (i.e., admits a section formula_116, as a homomorphism of Lie algebras), then formula_7 is said to be a semidirect product of formula_113 and formula_74, formula_120. See also semidirect sum of Lie algebras.

=== Derivations ===
For an algebra &quot;A&quot; over a field &quot;F&quot;, a &quot;derivation&quot; of &quot;A&quot; over &quot;F&quot; is a linear map formula_121 that satisfies the Leibniz rule
:formula_122
for all formula_123. (The definition makes sense for a possibly non-associative algebra.) Given two derivations formula_124 and formula_125, their commutator formula_126 is again a derivation. This operation makes the space formula_127 of all derivations of &quot;A&quot; over &quot;F&quot; into a Lie algebra.

Informally speaking, the space of derivations of &quot;A&quot; is the Lie algebra of the automorphism group of &quot;A&quot;. (This is literally true when the automorphism group is a Lie group, for example when &quot;F&quot; is the real numbers and &quot;A&quot; has finite dimension as a vector space.) For this reason, spaces of derivations are a natural way to construct Lie algebras: they are the &quot;infinitesimal automorphisms&quot; of &quot;A&quot;. Indeed, writing out the condition that
:formula_128
(where 1 denotes the identity map on &quot;A&quot;) gives exactly the definition of &quot;D&quot; being a derivation.

Example: the Lie algebra of vector fields. Let &quot;A&quot; be the ring formula_129 of smooth functions on a smooth manifold &quot;X&quot;. Then a derivation of &quot;A&quot; over formula_130 is equivalent to a vector field on &quot;X&quot;. (A vector field &quot;v&quot; gives a derivation of the space of smooth functions by differentiating functions in the direction of &quot;v&quot;.) This makes the space formula_131 of vector fields into a Lie algebra (see Lie bracket of vector fields). Informally speaking, formula_131 is the Lie algebra of the diffeomorphism group of &quot;X&quot;. So the Lie bracket of vector fields describes the non-commutativity of the diffeomorphism group. An action of a Lie group &quot;G&quot; on a manifold &quot;X&quot; determines a homomorphism of Lie algebras formula_133. (An example is illustrated below.)

A Lie algebra can be viewed as a non-associative algebra, and so each Lie algebra formula_7 over a field &quot;F&quot; determines its Lie algebra of derivations, formula_135. That is, a derivation of formula_7 is a linear map formula_137 such that
:formula_138.
The &quot;inner derivation&quot; associated to any formula_139 is the adjoint mapping formula_140 defined by formula_141. (This is a derivation as a consequence of the Jacobi identity.) That gives a homomorphism of Lie algebras, formula_142. The image formula_143 is an ideal in formula_135, and the Lie algebra of &quot;outer derivations&quot; is defined as the quotient Lie algebra, formula_145. (This is exactly analogous to the outer automorphism group of a group.) For a semisimple Lie algebra (defined below) over a field of characteristic zero, every derivation is inner. This is related to the theorem that the outer automorphism group of a semisimple Lie group is finite.

In contrast, an abelian Lie algebra has many outer derivations. Namely, for a vector space formula_46 with Lie bracket zero, the Lie algebra formula_147 can be identified with formula_55.

== Examples ==
=== Matrix Lie algebras ===
A matrix group is a Lie group consisting of invertible matrices, formula_149, where the group operation of &quot;G&quot; is matrix multiplication. The corresponding Lie algebra formula_1 is the space of matrices which are tangent vectors to &quot;G&quot; inside the linear space formula_151: this consists of derivatives of smooth curves in &quot;G&quot; at the identity matrix formula_152:
:formula_153
The Lie bracket of formula_7 is given by the commutator of matrices, formula_58. Given a Lie algebra formula_156, one can recover the Lie group as the subgroup generated by the matrix exponential of elements of formula_7. (To be precise, this gives the identity component of &quot;G&quot;, if &quot;G&quot; is not connected.) Here the exponential mapping formula_158 is defined by formula_159, which converges for every matrix formula_160.

The same comments apply to complex Lie subgroups of formula_161 and the complex matrix exponential, formula_162 (defined by the same formula).

Here are some matrix Lie groups and their Lie algebras.

* For a positive integer &quot;n&quot;, the special linear group formula_163 consists of all real matrices with determinant 1. This is the group of linear maps from formula_164 to itself that preserve volume and orientation. More abstractly, formula_163 is the commutator subgroup of the general linear group formula_166. Its Lie algebra formula_167 consists of all real matrices with trace 0. Similarly, one can define the analogous complex Lie group formula_168 and its Lie algebra formula_169.
* The orthogonal group formula_170 plays a basic role in geometry: it is the group of linear maps from formula_164 to itself that preserve the length of vectors. For example, rotations and reflections belong to formula_170. Equivalently, this is the group of &quot;n&quot; x &quot;n&quot; orthogonal matrices, meaning that formula_173, where formula_174 denotes the transpose of a matrix. The orthogonal group has two connected components; the identity component is called the &quot;special orthogonal group&quot; formula_175, consisting of the orthogonal matrices with determinant 1. Both groups have the same Lie algebra formula_176, the subspace of skew-symmetric matrices in formula_59 (formula_178). See also infinitesimal rotations with skew-symmetric matrices.
:The complex orthogonal group formula_179, its identity component formula_180, and the Lie algebra formula_181 are given by the same formulas applied to &quot;n&quot; x &quot;n&quot; complex matrices. Equivalently, formula_179 is the subgroup of formula_62 that preserves the standard symmetric bilinear form on formula_184.
* The unitary group formula_185 is the subgroup of formula_62 that preserves the length of vectors in formula_184 (with respect to the standard Hermitian inner product). Equivalently, this is the group of &quot;n&quot; × &quot;n&quot; unitary matrices (satisfying formula_188, where formula_189 denotes the conjugate transpose of a matrix). Its Lie algebra formula_190 consists of the skew-hermitian matrices in formula_61 (formula_192). This is a Lie algebra over formula_130, not over formula_194. (Indeed, &quot;i&quot; times a skew-hermitian matrix is hermitian, rather than skew-hermitian.) Likewise, the unitary group formula_185 is a real Lie subgroup of the complex Lie group formula_62. For example, formula_197 is the circle group, and its Lie algebra (from this point of view) is formula_198.
* The special unitary group formula_199 is the subgroup of matrices with determinant 1 in formula_185. Its Lie algebra formula_41 consists of the skew-hermitian matrices with trace zero.
*The symplectic group formula_202 is the subgroup of formula_203 that preserves the standard alternating bilinear form on formula_204. Its Lie algebra is the symplectic Lie algebra formula_205.
*The classical Lie algebras are those listed above, along with variants over any field.

=== Two dimensions ===
Some Lie algebras of low dimension are described here. See the classification of low-dimensional real Lie algebras for further examples.

* There is a unique nonabelian Lie algebra formula_7 of dimension 2 over any field &quot;F&quot;, up to isomorphism. Here formula_7 has a basis formula_208 for which the bracket is given by formula_209. (This determines the Lie bracket completely, because the axioms imply that formula_210 and formula_211.) Over the real numbers, formula_7 can be viewed as the Lie algebra of the Lie group formula_213 of affine transformations of the real line, formula_214.

:The affine group &quot;G&quot; can be identified with the group of matrices
::formula_215
:under matrix multiplication, with formula_216, formula_217. Its Lie algebra is the Lie subalgebra formula_7 of formula_219 consisting of all matrices
::formula_220
:In these terms, the basis above for formula_7 is given by the matrices
::formula_222

:For any field formula_18, the 1-dimensional subspace formula_224 is an ideal in the 2-dimensional Lie algebra formula_7, by the formula formula_226. Both of the Lie algebras formula_224 and formula_228 are abelian (because 1-dimensional). In this sense, formula_7 can be broken into abelian &quot;pieces&quot;, meaning that it is solvable (though not nilpotent), in the terminology below.

